Cairn-Keeper elder Toreth Gael proposed the warden tribunal system at the Oath-Crossing negotiations between Kowloon and Midgaard.
Kowloon's envoys had demanded binding arbitration clauses enforceable by the Jade Magistracy; Midgaard's wardens refused single-city jurisdictional control over neutral ground.
Toreth Gael proposed a compromise: disputes settled at standing stones under forest witness judgment, both parties presenting before assembled neutral observers, verdicts carved into the stone.
This hybrid combined Kowloon's documentary requirement with the forest's communal witness tradition.
It became the foundation of the modern warden tribunal system, still practiced at the Oath-Crossing stones.
Toreth Gael represented the Cairn-Keepers, one of three pre-civic peoples of the Great Northern Forest — megalith ancestor-communion practitioners.
His contribution was mediatory: finding procedural synthesis that each faction could accept without abandoning its core principle.
The verdict-carved-in-stone practice simultaneously satisfies Kowloon's documentary requirement, Midgaard's neutral-witness requirement, and the Cairn-Keepers' ancestor-communication practice.
The warden tribunal system is the only inter-city dispute-resolution mechanism that functions in the forest without either city claiming jurisdiction.
Warden training curricula in all five cities include study of the Oath-Crossing negotiations as a primary case study in multi-authority mediation.
Toreth Gael is the rare historical figure whose legacy is the system he created rather than the faction he represented.

